Jehos wrote:How soon until the next one arrives? Maybe that one will speak better English.If not, see if you can recruit one of the bilingual hockey players to stay with you also.We've got more trickling in over the next few days. (Essentially, they're arriving whenever the team they play for is eliminated from the play-offs.) We made sure that we'll have at least 1 or 2 players that speak English, but we'll have 2-3 that speak no English most likely, plus we are hosting homemade dinners for all 15ish players most nights until early May.So, no question that learning some minimal Russian (at least how to pronounce Cyrillic -- thanks for the link dferrantino) will be needed to be a descent, friendly host.A couple Vodka questions:1) Is there a standard drinking age in Russian culture? (Players will range from 16 to mid-twenties.)2) What does Russian culture say about athletes drinking during training? (IIUC, the American prohibitionists attitude towards alcohol and athletic training is not universal worldwide.) Obviously, these are serious enough athletes that they are each spending many thousands of dollars to come to America to train with top coaches for several weeks of their off-season. I know they (probably) won't want to down a bottle of Vodka before waking up for conditioning training at 8AM the next day, but if a couple drinks is the norm, I don't want them to feel like they are being forced into teetotalism.
