svdsinner wrote:naphini wrote:chalex wrote:Sounds like you could have a computer in the common room with Google Translate open on it. All the time.Do that. But you'll need to install the Cyrillic keyboard (Russian layout) on your computer. The traditional Russian layout has nothing whatever to do with the Qwerty layout, and that's probably what they'll be used to. If they can touch-type you won't even need stickers. Otherwise, you could get a Cyrillic sticker set for the keyboard, and you should have no trouble communicating, albeit slowly. I can't imagine you'll be able to learn enough Russian in a short amount of time to be able to say or understand much more than, "Hello," "Goodbye," and, "And now, I am to drink with the guy who send the dogs at the local residents in Zambia. This is not stair related. A monkey is on the table."This is dead on. I know I won't be able to learn Russian, per se, but with this Cyrillic alphabet thing, I can't even get a translation and attempt to pronounce it. All other foreign language speakers I've been around at least showed the courtesy of speaking languages that at least use normal letters that I can at least try to pronounce.Would it be feasible to learn how to pronounce words spelled with Cyrillic letters, or is Russian one of those languages (like English) that spelling doesn't always lead to pronunciation?On the contrary: Russian letters are consistently pronounced the same way almost 100% of the time. The only major exception is that sometimes an 'o' at the end of a word is pronounced like an 'a', e.g. "thank you" is spelled "спасибо" but pronounced "spa-see-ba" (with the emphasis on the "see").
